T1  - Can We Defend Subjective Performance Appraisal? (A Comment)
AU  - Chung, Kae H.
Y1  - 1969/12/01
PY  - 1969
DA  - 1969/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/254742
DO  - 10.5465/254742
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 507
EP  - 510
VL  - 12
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article presents a comment on an earlier article titled ?In Defense of Executive Appraisal,? by George H. Labovitz in the September 1969 issue of this publication. The author agrees that executives should be judged on their ability to interact, but takes issue with the apparent theoretical gap in the assumption that interaction correlates to the level of performance or the achievement of organizational goals. Second, the author argues that the attainment of personal goals does not necessarily correlate with the achievement of organizational goals. Finally, the author argues that subjective performance criteria should be distinguished from subjective appraisal. The author discusses the fairness of quantitative assessment.
AB  - The article presents a comment on an earlier article titled ?In Defense of Executive Appraisal,? by George H. Labovitz in the September 1969 issue of this publication. The author agrees that executives should be judged on their ability to interact, but takes issue with the apparent theoretical gap in the assumption that interaction correlates to the level of performance or the achievement of organizational goals. Second, the author argues that the attainment of personal goals does not necessarily correlate with the achievement of organizational goals. Finally, the author argues that subjective performance criteria should be distinguished from subjective appraisal. The author discusses the fairness of quantitative assessment.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/254742
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/254742
Y2  - 2026/04/24
